name: getDisplayName

protocol.member: getDisplayName(java.lang.String ID, boolean daylight, int style, java.util.Locale locale)
protocol.comment: Returns a name for the given time zone ID that's suitable for presentation to the user in the specified locale. The given time zone ID is "GMT" or one of the names defined using "Zone" entries in the "tz database", a public domain time zone database at ftp://elsiemethod_0method_1method_2/pub/. The data of this database is contained in a file whose name starts with "tzdata", and the specification of the data format is part of the zicmethod_6 man page, which is contained in a file whose name starts with "tzcode".  If daylight is true, the method should return a name appropriate for daylight saving time even if the specified time zone has not observed daylight saving time in the past.

signature: getGenericDisplayName(java.lang.String ID, int style, java.util.Locale locale)
name: getGenericDisplayName

protocol.member: getGenericDisplayName(java.lang.String ID, int style, java.util.Locale locale)
protocol.comment: Returns a generic name for the given time zone ID that's suitable for presentation to the user in the specified locale. Generic time zone names are neutral from standard time and daylight saving time. For example, "PT" is the short generic name of time zone ID America/Los_Angeles, while its short standard time and daylight saving time names are "PST" and "PDT", respectively. Refer to method_0 getDisplayName for valid time zone IDs. The default implementation of this method returns null.
